# Role-lane registry — one lane per line.
#
# Format: <lane-name> [parallel-of:<main-role>]
# - Lines starting with '#' and blank lines are ignored.
# - A main role has no 'parallel-of:' marker.
# - A parallel-main lane declares its discipline twin with 'parallel-of:<main-role>'.
#   Parallel-main lanes carry full main-role authority (structural decisions,
#   design reports, skill edits) — they are a second seat at the discipline,
#   not a subordinate lane.
# - A specialized lane (e.g. cluster-operator, nota-designer) is a structural
#   role with a token-vector identity in the typed registry (e.g. [Cluster
#   Operator], [Nota Designer]) and a specialized scope within its main role's
#   discipline. Carries Structural authority. Appears bare in the bash format
#   for now; the typed persona-orchestrate registry handles the role-vector
#   shape natively. Ordinal prefixes (second-, third-) copy the whole following
#   role per spirit record 174 — so a second cluster-operator becomes
#   second-cluster-operator, not second-operator with cluster scope.
#
# Per spirit record 920 (Maximum, 2026-05-27): the prior <role>-assistant
# and <role>-specialist suffixes are RETIRED workspace-wide. Additional
# capacity in a role is added as second-<role> / third-<role>, etc.
#
# This file is a transitional bash-readable format. The destination is
# orchestrate/roles.nota — a typed Nota record read by a Rust-rewritten
# tools/orchestrate.

operator
pi-operator                       parallel-of:operator
second-operator                   parallel-of:operator
cluster-operator
cloud-operator
cloud-maintainer
maintainer                       parallel-of:system-maintainer
designer
second-designer                   parallel-of:designer
third-designer                    parallel-of:designer
nota-designer
system-designer
cloud-designer
system-operator
system-maintainer
poet
editor
videographer
assistant
counselor
